00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:25.638
[suspensful jazzy percussion]

00:03:25.638 --> 00:03:32.400
Natalie Nourigat observed in her Guardian column,
"The use of propaganda is ancient,

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:37.260
but never before has there been the
technology to so effectively disseminate it."

00:03:37.260 --> 00:03:40.320
And that's kind of the crux of the issue
we'll be exploring today,

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:43.740
but as always, we have to know how we got here&nbsp;

00:03:43.740 --> 00:03:47.340
to truly understand the 'here'&nbsp;
that we're dealing with.

00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:51.300
It shouldn't be surprising at all to hear
that propaganda and misinformation

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:56.100
aren't remotely new problems,
and are, in fact, very ancient ones.

00:03:56.100 --> 00:03:59.100
From the age of the Romans,
when Emperor Octavian used coins

00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:03.360
to disseminate catchy slogans
painting Antony as a drunk womanizer;

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:08.640
to the 6th Century AD, when Procopius of
Caesaria used a treatise called

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:12.120
Secret History to spread lies about
Emperor Justinian and his wife,

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:14.760
and gain favor under the new emperor.

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:18.960
Historical misinformation is,&nbsp;
after all, inherently political.

00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:23.280
Joanna M Burkhardt writes in
'Combating Fake News in the Digital Age,'

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:28.380
"Knowledge is power. Those controlling knowledge,
information, and the means to disseminate

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:33.180
information became group leaders, with
privileges that others in the group did not have.

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:37.200
In many early state societies,
remnants of the perks of leadership

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:40.920
remain - pyramids, castles, lavish
household goods, and more."

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:45.300
But naturally, misinformation gets a
massive boost by the inventions

00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:50.100
of new and radical innovations to
media and information delivery.

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:54.360
When the Gutenberg printing press
was invented in 1493, it sparked

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:58.620
not only the beginning of mass media,
but a sharp rise in literacy.

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:03.960
Literacy doesn't always come coupled with
media literacy, however; as we well know today.

00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:09.420
Many readers were still, and still are,
vulnerable to lies and being too trusting

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:13.080
of authors that they deemed to be
trustworthy, for one reason or another.

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:18.300
As I discussed in my video on Julie d'Aubigny,
many writers and memoirists in

00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:24.000
the 17th to 18th centuries had absolutely
no reason to not lie in their works.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.600
After all, who was going to&nbsp;
fact check them to the masses?

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:32.460
And frankly, embellishing stories with made-up
details certainly made them sell better.

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:36.600
That's not to say that no one recognized
that this was a serious issue, though.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:42.120
In 1710, Jonathan Swift published an essay
titled, 'The Art of Political Lying,'

00:05:42.120 --> 00:05:44.280
in which he ominously proclaimed,&nbsp;

00:05:44.280 --> 00:05:47.940
"Falsehood flies, and truth&nbsp;
comes limping after it,

00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:52.440
so that when men come to be undeceived,
it is too late; the jest is over,

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:54.300
and the tale hath had its effect."

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:58.380
Over time, these lies became part
of historical canon - repeated over

00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:02.580
and over and over; and are often
only recently being double-checked,

00:06:02.580 --> 00:06:04.920
or even questioned by historians.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:08.400
And these issues, of course,
eventually led to the first

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:12.780
large-scale news hoax in 1835:
the Great Moon Hoax,

00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:17.520
in which The New York Sun newspaper
published six articles claiming that

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:19.740
life had been discovered on the moon.

00:06:19.740 --> 00:06:26.520
These articles included huge illustrations showing
strange bat-like aliens, unicorns, and more.

00:06:26.520 --> 00:06:30.060
And, obviously, a lot of people read this
and were like,

00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:33.480
'Oh, my god! The newspaper is&nbsp;
printing it, so it must be true!"

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:37.740
Tragically, there are no bat people&nbsp;
or blue unicorns on the moon.

00:06:37.740 --> 00:06:41.100
But this wouldn't be the last time
people in the 1800s would

00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:44.100
shamelessly publish fiction
under the guise of truth.

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:50.640
In 1844, Edgar Allan Poe wrote an article
claiming that someone had crossed the

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:53.460
Atlantic in three days in a
hot air balloon, and then

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:56.880
proceeded to write at least six more
fake news stories in his lifetime,

00:06:56.880 --> 00:07:01.080
each time causing havoc for reporters
and the readers who believed the stories.

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:06.000
Which would be really funny, if I didn't
know where shit like this led to, so.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:07.980
No. Bad Edgar.

00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:13.920
And then Washington Irving, the author
famous for writing stories like 'Sleepy Hollow'

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:17.280
and 'Rip Van Winkle,' also
fancied himself a historian.

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:20.640
The problem is, many of his history
books were filled with

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:23.220
romantic fiction played off as facts.

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:26.520
The most famous case that he created
came from his book on the

00:07:26.520 --> 00:07:30.900
life of Christopher Columbus, in which
he claimed that Europeans believe

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:34.920
that the Earth was flat until Columbus
proved that it was actually round.

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:39.000
As I talked about in my video on
medieval myths, the Europeans of

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.420
the Middle Ages actually didn't
believe the Earth was flat.

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:45.960
They had the science and mathematics
to know that it was round,

00:07:45.960 --> 00:07:48.900
and depicted it as such in many illustrations.

00:07:48.900 --> 00:07:54.000
But the Flat Earth myth fell in easily
with the Victorians idea that

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:59.460
the Middle Ages was the Dark Ages, and all
medieval people were horrible and stupid.

00:07:59.460 --> 00:08:03.960
So this lie got repeated and reinforced
throughout the 19th century,

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:09.000
until it ended up becoming a commonly held
and accepted belief about medieval times.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:14.340
The Victorians were eager to paint that era as
the Dark Ages because it followed

00:08:14.340 --> 00:08:20.940
the Enlightenment idea of Progressivism: that
progress is linear, and every era is inherently

00:08:20.940 --> 00:08:23.700
better than the last, in every possible way.

00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:26.760
And as a result, the Victorians believed

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:33.300
that they were a superior society - just, uh,
don't look at all the colonization and slavery

00:08:33.300 --> 00:08:34.680
and poverty happening over there.

00:08:34.680 --> 00:08:38.040
But you can see how that would
give writers and historians an

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:40.500
incentive to lie about the past, right?

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:43.440
The printing press wasn't&nbsp;
the end of media evolution.

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:47.520
With each new invention: the radio,
the film camera, television,

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:52.980
and now the internet, the ease with which fake
history can be consumed and disseminated

00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:56.160
has only grown more and more powerful.

00:08:56.160 --> 00:09:00.540
In the age of the Internet, it's&nbsp;
now easier than ever to spread lies.

00:09:00.540 --> 00:09:03.060
Before, at least, you needed&nbsp;
some sort of credentials.

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:07.440
You had to be a writer, or someone of note,
or had some kind of access to

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:10.500
the rare and coveted tools
to access the masses.

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:13.920
Now, for better or for worse,
these tools are in the hands

00:09:13.920 --> 00:09:16.920
of every single person with&nbsp;
access to the internet.

00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:20.940
Anyone can, in a matter of minutes,
create an account on Twitter,

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:26.220
or TikTok, or YouTube, and post a video or
tweet, claiming some kind of fact or history,

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:30.900
with no sources cited;&nbsp;
maliciously or knowingly, or not.

00:09:30.900 --> 00:09:34.440
And potentially hundreds,&nbsp;
or thousands, or millions&nbsp;

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:37.980
of people will see and possibly believe it.

00:09:37.980 --> 00:09:43.860
This, the conundrum we find ourselves in today,
is an issue more serious than we realize.

00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:49.320
Few people understand how serious it is than,
well, people like me and many

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:54.780
other historical educators online. Our job is
very serious, because I understand

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:57.300
how easy it is to fall for lies online.

00:09:57.300 --> 00:10:00.600
Actually, that was one of the reasons
I made my channel in the first place.

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:04.560
I got really, really sick of going on
Twitter every day, and seeing

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:08.460
people make huge threads about history;
filled with lies or misinformation,

00:10:08.460 --> 00:10:14.340
with no sources or shoddy sources;
but worded so confidently

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:15.660
that people believed them.

00:10:15.660 --> 00:10:20.220
From issues as benign as the old claim
that corsets were woman-hating

00:10:20.220 --> 00:10:25.800
murderous death cages, to issues as
serious as lies about the Holocaust.

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:29.640
Every day it was something, and
every time I clicked on the thread,

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:34.800
I would see dozens, if not hundreds of
people, uncritically taking it as truth.

00:10:34.800 --> 00:10:38.760
And I got really, really upset and scared.

00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:40.200
You don't know that person.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:43.800
If you, like me, ask them for&nbsp;
their sources, a lot of the time

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:47.220
you'd get a response with some&nbsp;
variation of "just trust me bro."

00:10:47.220 --> 00:10:50.324
Or you'd get ignored, or they'd lash out at you.

00:10:50.324 --> 00:10:52.260
[Buster Baxter: "You really&nbsp;
think someone would do that?

00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:54.540
Just go on the internet and tell lies?"]

00:10:54.540 --> 00:10:57.540
That's why all my videos have&nbsp;
my comprehensive sources listed,

00:10:57.540 --> 00:11:04.380
and I spend days, and days, and -days- crawling&nbsp;
through my sources. trying my best to vet them.

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.780
And even then, sometimes I slip up.

00:11:06.780 --> 00:11:09.780
And if that happens despite the
amount of research I do,

00:11:09.780 --> 00:11:13.800
imagine how easy it is for someone
who does basically no research at all

00:11:13.800 --> 00:11:18.060
to shit out a video, spouting some completely
buck wild story about history,

00:11:18.060 --> 00:11:24.240
and have it reach a city's worth of people.
And few places online harbor this

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:27.990
as easily as the internet's
misinformation darling, TikTok

00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:28.860
[music: contemplative piano solo]

00:11:28.860 --> 00:11:37.440
I don't know what to blame for&nbsp;
how popular these videos get.

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:41.160
I can't just say it's because&nbsp;
TikTok's user base is mostly kids,

00:11:41.160 --> 00:11:44.940
because a lot of people I see&nbsp;
falling for these videos are adults,

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:48.180
and almost all the people&nbsp;
making these videos are adults.

00:11:48.180 --> 00:11:52.140
So is it because people on TikTok&nbsp;
are inherently more gullible?

00:11:52.140 --> 00:11:54.540
I don't know. Maybe?

00:11:54.540 --> 00:11:59.880
I hate to say that because I, too, have&nbsp;
literally fallen for fake stuff on there before.

00:11:59.880 --> 00:12:02.280
I am not immune to propaganda.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:05.760
I think the difference has a lot&nbsp;
to do with the fact that on TikTok,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:10.140
you're not typically seeing like,&nbsp;
professionals and fancy productions.

00:12:10.140 --> 00:12:12.840
You're seeing regular people in their homes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.840 --> 00:12:15.780
excitedly sharing something&nbsp;
they just learned with you.

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:18.660
And I can definitely see the appeal of that.

00:12:18.660 --> 00:12:21.000
That's what my own videos are too, in a way.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.320
But these TikTok videos make it easier
to trust the people making them

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:29.160
because it kind of tricks your brain
into seeing this info as being given

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:31.800
to you by a friend in an intimate conversation.

00:12:31.800 --> 00:12:34.500
These folks seem cool and personable,

00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:37.260
and you can see their face,
and you want to trust them.

00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:41.520
And like, most people aren't going to sit down and
read a brick of a book every day like I do.

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:44.760
And there's also the complicated&nbsp;
factor of like, people wanting to trust

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:48.660
"regular people" rather than academic,&nbsp;
inaccessible, "fancy pants guys"

00:12:48.660 --> 00:12:53.280
because a lot of folks online&nbsp;
really easily fall for the idea

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:57.660
that the "higher-ups" are trying&nbsp;
to hide some great secret from you.

00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:02.100
And that's where you get stuff&nbsp;
like the Helen Keller conspiracy.

00:13:02.100 --> 00:13:05.340
The Helen Keller conspiracy&nbsp;
started sometime around May 2020,

00:13:05.340 --> 00:13:09.960
when a user on TikTok started&nbsp;
using #HelenKellerWasntReal

00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:13.800
which then drifted over to&nbsp;
Twitter, when Daniel Kunka tweeted

00:13:13.800 --> 00:13:16.920
that his younger relatives&nbsp;
had insisted to him that

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:19.320
"Helen Keller was a fraud who didn't exist."

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:25.020
Almost every video on TikTok advancing
this conspiracy usually gets a few people

00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:29.400
in the comments challenging it, which
usually get the, 'okay go away boomer' reply.

00:13:29.400 --> 00:13:32.880
Many commenters also recount&nbsp;
fighting with their teachers about it

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:36.660
which enforces the idea of their&nbsp;
"beliefs being suppressed."

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:40.620
The root of this conspiracy is&nbsp;
centered on the ableist belief that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:44.700
if Helen Keller really was deaf and&nbsp;
blind, she couldn't have done all that.

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:48.060
Haben Girma, a deaf-blind&nbsp;
human rights lawyer, writes:

00:13:48.060 --> 00:13:50.340
"The videos may have started as jokes,

00:13:50.340 --> 00:13:53.280
but that doesn't change the fact that&nbsp;
they are harming disabled people...

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:58.440
Nearly every disabled person has been told,
at one time or another, 'You're faking it.'"

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:02.340
Keller was accused of being a fake
and a liar even in her own lifetime,

00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:07.200
and even frequently by people who had
previously sided with and protected her.

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:11.700
Any disabled person knows just how easy
it is for folks to give up on,

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:14.040
or turn on us when it becomes convenient.

00:14:14.040 --> 00:14:17.820
For example, she had largely leftist
and progressive political beliefs

00:14:17.820 --> 00:14:22.680
and intended to be involved in activism,
but was often disregarded because

00:14:22.680 --> 00:14:26.580
people believed her limited development,
whatever the f*** that means,

00:14:26.580 --> 00:14:29.940
meant that she was too easily
influenced by outside voices.

