00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:48.540
"cl*toris healer."

00:28:48.540 --> 00:28:52.260
I'm not even going to bother refuting
any of this, because it's literally

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:57.660
not worth my time, but if you're interested,
I promise if you Google 'momlennial Rome'

00:28:57.660 --> 00:29:01.380
you'll find a million videos from
2021 fighting this woman.

00:29:01.380 --> 00:29:05.040
Donna has since, it seems, deleted her
account and remade a new one

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:10.080
called momlennial_returns, where she's
still trying to harp on the Rome isn't real thing,

00:29:10.080 --> 00:29:13.740
now doubling down and saying that
what she actually means is that

00:29:13.740 --> 00:29:20.460
there is no single Roman culture, which is
not at all what she originally said, but okay.

00:29:20.460 --> 00:29:20.940
Anyway.

00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:25.860
But the truth here is, to be frank,
Donna, and many creators like her,

00:29:25.860 --> 00:29:30.900
is most likely a grifter. I think this
was summed up incredibly well

00:29:30.900 --> 00:29:35.700
in this TikTok by Dr. MJ Pardon,
which I will show you in its entirety.

00:29:35.700 --> 00:29:39.000
["...but the church would never
do that to white people!"

00:29:39.720 --> 00:29:42.120
"Stop what you're doing, and just for
a moment, reflect on your

00:29:42.120 --> 00:29:45.240
immediate reaction to that, especially
in the context of a creator complaining

00:29:45.240 --> 00:29:47.640
that these are the kind of comments
that she keeps getting on her videos.

00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:51.000
This is a great way to start the video,
because we're automatically on her side.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:52.980
You certainly don't want to be
on the side of the people who are

00:29:52.980 --> 00:29:54.540
disagreeing with her in her comment section.

00:29:55.140 --> 00:29:57.780
Um, because first of all, sounds like
those people are kind of racist.

00:29:57.780 --> 00:30:00.120
Um, and second of all, it sounds like
those people are just regurgitating

00:30:00.120 --> 00:30:02.100
this narrative that they've been
spoon-fed by the church,

00:30:02.100 --> 00:30:06.600
and we certainly all want to be pushing back
against oppressive institutions that are

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:08.220
seeking to control the historical narrative.

00:30:08.220 --> 00:30:12.060
And this is not the only thing that's really smart
about this video, and her videos in general.

00:30:12.060 --> 00:30:15.012
You may notice that her videos
are all these sort of short,

00:30:15.012 --> 00:30:17.040
very incredulous, kind of punchy debunks.

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:20.940
Or like, how am I the only one who sees this,
like, sheeple you need to wake up.

00:30:21.480 --> 00:30:24.720
Um, but she never really fully explains
her overarching worldview

00:30:24.720 --> 00:30:28.140
or how these different little&nbsp;
points all connect together,

00:30:28.140 --> 00:30:30.300
and that's on purpose,
because that drives engagement.

00:30:30.300 --> 00:30:31.920
You then have to ask.

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:34.860
Also, if she started off her video
with the statement,

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:39.720
The Roman Empire, the entire Roman Empire,
as well as the entire Latin language,

00:30:39.720 --> 00:30:43.560
was invented in the 15th century,
by the Spanish Inquisition.

00:30:43.560 --> 00:30:47.400
And that's a historical narrative that has
always just been protected by "the Church,"

00:30:47.400 --> 00:30:50.520
I assume she means the Catholic Church, but
she always just sort of says the Church. Anyway.

00:30:50.520 --> 00:30:54.900
The point is, if she led with that, she would
probably lose a lot of viewers pretty fast.

00:30:54.900 --> 00:30:57.000
But she doesn't lead with that.
She sort of entices you in,

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:00.120
leads you down the path, and then
eventually, when it's time,

00:31:00.120 --> 00:31:04.200
she presents you with sort of
the large conspiracy theory.

00:31:05.160 --> 00:31:08.880
Tons of people have debunked this,
um, but also we've been here before.

00:31:08.880 --> 00:31:12.540
Tons of people debunked when she was talking
about Alexander the Great being a woman,

00:31:12.540 --> 00:31:16.320
or all of her claims about the historical Jesus,
um, it sort of comes in waves.

00:31:16.860 --> 00:31:19.920
But when you hear people say or make
comments on her videos of like,

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:22.560
oh, I'm sort of having trouble following this.
Can you maybe just make one video

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:24.660
explaining how sort of all your&nbsp;
da-, ideas connect together?

00:31:24.660 --> 00:31:25.920
Or, this is sort of unclear.

00:31:26.700 --> 00:31:28.500
Um, that's a feature, not a bug.

00:31:30.180 --> 00:31:33.000
Um, that's sort of part of her strategy
for creating these videos.

00:31:34.020 --> 00:31:38.220
When I initially made a sort of "debunk"
sort of video for her views, I wrote

00:31:38.220 --> 00:31:41.100
a comment saying, you know, I'm gonna
feel really stupid if it turns out that

00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:42.720
this is all just elaborate performance art,

00:31:42.720 --> 00:31:45.720
and you know what? I feel really stupid.

00:31:45.720 --> 00:31:51.480
And to be clear, it's not performance art.
It's just really strategic content creation.

00:31:52.260 --> 00:31:54.540
And she's really good at it, I mean,
she has almost 10,000 followers.

00:31:54.540 --> 00:31:55.380
She's getting a lot of engagement.

00:31:55.380 --> 00:31:58.140
I'm, of course, feeding into that
because I'm a dumbass, um,

00:31:58.140 --> 00:32:00.060
but you know, it's not hard to find her LinkedIn.

00:32:00.060 --> 00:32:04.200
Maybe this is my conspiracy theory time now?
Anyway, put on your tinfoil hats, people!

00:32:04.200 --> 00:32:08.220
Anyway, her LinkedIn - she describes
herself as "a seasoned

00:32:08.220 --> 00:32:11.100
digital media expert with 10+ years
experience in content strategy."

00:32:11.100 --> 00:32:14.160
She has a lot of presence online in
different forms of content creation,

00:32:14.160 --> 00:32:16.200
And you know what, she's really good at it."]

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:21.060
We may never know 100% for sure what her
true deal is, but regardless,

00:32:21.060 --> 00:32:25.560
just don't go giving her a hate follow,
or comments, or anything

00:32:25.560 --> 00:32:28.260
boosting her algorithm.
It's not worth it.

00:32:28.260 --> 00:32:32.940
Regardless, if you see someone online
"teaching history" with no sources,

00:32:32.940 --> 00:32:36.660
and you ask them for sources, and they
ignore, block, or get mad at you,

00:32:37.440 --> 00:32:40.560
maybe just disregard everything
you just heard them say.

00:32:41.280 --> 00:32:45.240
So all of this junk going down
on TikTok is frustrating enough.

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:48.180
Some of it is perpetuated on purpose,
some not.

00:32:48.180 --> 00:32:52.500
But what happens when someone
sets out to tell a fictional story

00:32:52.500 --> 00:32:57.360
and completely loses control of it,
because it wasn't formatted like one?

00:32:57.360 --> 00:33:02.280
What happens when you accidentally
weaponize the pain of lost LGBT history?

00:33:02.280 --> 00:33:05.829
[music: melancholy woodwinds]

00:33:05.829 --> 00:33:08.399
Disclaimer: this one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:10.860
isn't TikTok,
but I think it's still relevant to the point.

00:33:10.860 --> 00:33:17.220
In 2018, a Twitter user named Guillem Clua
began writing a long, very long, Twitter

00:33:17.220 --> 00:33:21.240
thread talking about how; while visiting
a cemetery in Sighișoara, Romania;

00:33:21.240 --> 00:33:25.860
he chanced upon a World War One gravestone
where two men are buried together.

00:33:25.860 --> 00:33:28.440
Emil Muller and Xaver Sumer.

00:33:28.440 --> 00:33:33.120
The thread, now marked with hashtag
#EmilYXaver went on to, in real time,

00:33:33.120 --> 00:33:38.700
detail Guillem's journey discovering this story
behind these two mysterious soldiers.

00:33:38.700 --> 00:33:42.180
He found out that the two men went to high
school together in their small town.

00:33:42.180 --> 00:33:46.800
He posted photos of his investigating, the
locations he was visiting around the city,

00:33:46.800 --> 00:33:48.660
following clue after clue.

00:33:48.660 --> 00:33:51.960
And over time, a heart-wrenching&nbsp;
story takes shape.

00:33:51.960 --> 00:33:57.300
He discovers that Emil and Xaver were lovers
forced to be apart by their families,

00:33:57.300 --> 00:34:01.980
and they were reunited just before they were
shortly separated once more by death.

00:34:01.980 --> 00:34:05.100
Guillem wrote, "I finally put&nbsp;
a face on the two soldiers.

00:34:05.100 --> 00:34:09.600
I put their photographs next to each other,
but their gazes are riveted on mine.

00:34:09.600 --> 00:34:13.320
And through space and time, I see
them in a common supplication:

00:34:13.320 --> 00:34:16.140
"Tell our story or we will never exist.""

00:34:16.140 --> 00:34:20.100
I saw this thread as it was coming out in 2018,
and as I read through it,

00:34:20.100 --> 00:34:23.640
my heart felt trapped in my throat.
I remember laying in bed,

00:34:23.640 --> 00:34:26.700
reading it on the verge of tears,
because as Guillem visited

00:34:26.700 --> 00:34:31.140
local residents connecting hints and clues,
reading through letters and paintings,

00:34:31.140 --> 00:34:37.140
watching this hidden story unfold, a love
lost to time, finally resurfacing

00:34:37.140 --> 00:34:40.680
a hundred years later - as
many before us have said,

00:34:40.680 --> 00:34:43.680
Emil and Xaver were just born too soon.

00:34:43.680 --> 00:34:47.880
It's exactly what made me so passionate
about queer history in the first place.

00:34:47.880 --> 00:34:52.140
Uncovering, reinterpreting, and loving
these histories is so valuable.

00:34:52.140 --> 00:34:57.000
It gives our community a past to hold onto,
and gives us the opportunity to

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:00.540
posthumously pay back
some much-deserved love

00:35:00.540 --> 00:35:02.820
and acknowledgment to those
who came before us.

00:35:02.820 --> 00:35:08.580
It's extremely grueling, difficult,
emotionally-taxing work that is

00:35:08.580 --> 00:35:10.680
frequently met with
severe backlash.

00:35:10.680 --> 00:35:15.660
So finding stories like this is like
finding a diamond in a muddy river.

00:35:15.660 --> 00:35:17.580
It's like one in a million.

00:35:17.580 --> 00:35:21.060
A story like this is every
queer historian's dream.

00:35:22.440 --> 00:35:25.920
Except the story isn't true. It's just fiction.

00:35:25.920 --> 00:35:29.940
And Guillem Clua was extremely open about it,
after the fact.

00:35:29.940 --> 00:35:32.340
The photos were planned and staged.

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:37.260
No one knows truly what the story behind these
two soldiers was, but they were real people.

00:35:37.260 --> 00:35:41.160
But because the thread wasn't in English,
and because it was paced out

00:35:41.160 --> 00:35:44.580
over the course of several days and
took the form of a Twitter thread,

00:35:44.580 --> 00:35:47.880
many people had absolutely no
idea that it was fake.

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:49.860
The headstone is real, after all.

00:35:49.860 --> 00:35:55.860
It was truly presented as fact, by accident,
and not by accident, somehow at once.

00:35:55.860 --> 00:36:00.360
Guillem didn't clearly acknowledge it
as fiction until the story was over.

00:36:00.360 --> 00:36:06.060
So obviously, people felt extremely
blindsided and betrayed.

00:36:06.060 --> 00:36:07.620
Because of course they did.

00:36:07.620 --> 00:36:11.220
Most of the great fervor surrounding
the story came from excited

00:36:11.220 --> 00:36:14.520
and hopeful LGBTQ readers - I
was one of them.

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:19.260
Having the wind knocked out of our sails
felt like the pain of lost history repeated.

00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:23.400
The queer community, like any marginalized
community with a history of having

00:36:23.400 --> 00:36:28.620
our stories forcibly erased, is an absurdly
bad community to use as the subject

00:36:28.620 --> 00:36:33.360
of a performance like this. Guillem himself
acknowledges this pain on one of his

00:36:33.360 --> 00:36:37.380
tweets in the thread: "Has their story not been
erased once, as has happened to

00:36:37.380 --> 00:36:40.680
millions of other soldiers who rest
under the soil of the whole continent?

00:36:40.680 --> 00:36:44.580
It was not fair for me to abandon them
again in that tomb of oblivion."

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:48.180
He was incredibly defensive when the
backlash began rolling in, too.

00:36:48.180 --> 00:36:51.120
Clapping back in a tweet&nbsp;
saying, 'Do you really think&nbsp;

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:53.700
LGBT history won't be taken seriously

00:36:53.700 --> 00:36:55.860
just because someone wrote a
love story on Twitter?

00:36:57.180 --> 00:36:59.160
Yeah, actually.

00:36:59.160 --> 00:37:04.260
Medieval queer historian Jonah Kaman wrote
a great article on this whole debacle,

00:37:04.260 --> 00:37:08.820
noting, "Yes, LGBT history won't be taken
seriously because of a Twitter story.

00:37:08.820 --> 00:37:11.160
When it all plays out on the
background of the history

00:37:11.160 --> 00:37:15.840
of queer historiography, 'making history'
itself, which for decades has been

00:37:15.840 --> 00:37:20.400
and still is being perceived as fake,
a liberal or deviant fantasy.

00:37:20.400 --> 00:37:24.000
You know what the term is for historical
fiction presented as truth? Propaganda.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:28.500
Queer history in and of itself has historically
been perceived as 'gay propaganda,'

00:37:28.500 --> 00:37:33.480
weaponized for the advance of the 'homosexual
agenda'; not an intellectual pursuit

00:37:33.480 --> 00:37:36.660
or a right of people to have&nbsp;
a past. Alex Drace-Francis&nbsp;

00:37:36.660 --> 00:37:38.640
makes a great point on Twitter that

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:41.100
'this story willfully&nbsp;
overwrites local experiences,&nbsp;

00:37:41.100 --> 00:37:42.600
imposes templates on them,

00:37:42.600 --> 00:37:45.900
makes still unheard stories harder to
research and recover.'"

00:37:45.900 --> 00:37:50.280
This story was very personal on an
even deeper level for Jonah, who was

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:54.600
born in Romania, not that far from where
the Emil Y Xaver story takes place.

00:37:54.600 --> 00:37:58.260
The story already hurt the&nbsp;
queer community at large.

00:37:58.260 --> 00:38:02.640
The sting is much more potent for
Eastern European queer folks who

00:38:02.640 --> 00:38:04.560
have a very unique struggle to deal with.

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:10.080
Incidents like Emil Y Xaver put a spotlight
on how fragile people's trust in history is.

00:38:10.080 --> 00:38:16.080
How easy it is to swindle online users into
believing a story if you frame it the right way,

00:38:16.080 --> 00:38:22.260
especially when the community you're targeting
is so, so hungry for a shared history of our own.

00:38:22.260 --> 00:38:26.700
A history that did exist and is out there, but is

00:38:26.700 --> 00:38:29.700
subject to an absurd level&nbsp;
of scrutiny at every turn.

00:38:29.700 --> 00:38:33.600
Seriously, every time I make videos
on LGBTQ historical figures,

00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:37.740
I get met with a flood of comments
from pissed off people, yelling at me

00:38:37.740 --> 00:38:41.820
for "lying about this person's Identity,"
or "turning everything gay."

00:38:41.820 --> 00:38:44.700
Even when I clearly have sources cited.

00:38:44.700 --> 00:38:49.020
People are already primed to disregard
queer history as fabricated,

00:38:49.020 --> 00:38:53.280
to scrutinize it with an intensity that they
never afford anything else.

00:38:53.280 --> 00:38:58.200
Incidents like Emil Y Xaver not only
make that problem worse, it also

00:38:58.200 --> 00:39:01.800
smacks the LGBTQ community with
one more smack of betrayal,

00:39:01.800 --> 00:39:06.540
letting us taste a story we had lost,
before tearing it away again.

00:39:06.540 --> 00:39:11.820
As an artist, I can sympathize with Guillem Clua's
instinct to protect the integrity of his art

00:39:11.820 --> 00:39:16.740
when defending himself against criticism,
especially since he himself is a gay man.

00:39:16.740 --> 00:39:19.320
But that doesn't erase the pain that it caused.

00:39:19.320 --> 00:39:24.780
Still, this is why you have to realize that
doing the work as a servant of history

00:39:24.780 --> 00:39:28.380
is long, hard, and extremely complicated.

00:39:28.380 --> 00:39:32.280
Sources need to not only be&nbsp;
cited, but carefully vetted.

00:39:32.280 --> 00:39:34.620
Details are easily missed or lost.

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:38.040
Doing research on a deadline
will wear you down until

00:39:38.040 --> 00:39:39.900
there's nothing left
but your bones.

00:39:40.826 --> 00:39:43.609
I have some bad news.

00:39:44.109 --> 00:39:46.776
[music: anxious, circusy accordion]

00:39:48.451 --> 00:39:52.062
Putting on my dunce hat&nbsp;
for this section. [giggles]

00:39:52.062 --> 00:39:54.600
I've spent this whole video dunking
on people who have spread

00:39:54.600 --> 00:39:57.600
historical misinformation, and yeah,
they all deserved it.

00:39:57.600 --> 00:40:00.360
But it would be ridiculous and
hypocritical of me to pretend

00:40:00.360 --> 00:40:01.980
that I've never f***** up myself.

00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:05.640
I mean, with the frequency that
I put out videos, and the sheer

00:40:05.640 --> 00:40:08.280
amount of information and essays and
books that I need to juggle.

00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:13.680
It's impossible to not take an L sometimes,
no matter how hard I try.

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:17.460
So, time to atone for my sins
by calling them out.

00:40:17.460 --> 00:40:21.120
In my first Victorian Medicine video
a few years ago, I said that

00:40:21.120 --> 00:40:24.480
Thomas Crapper invented the
flushing toilet. This is not true,

00:40:24.480 --> 00:40:28.980
despite the fact that it said so on a
seemingly reviewed UCLA website.

00:40:28.980 --> 00:40:31.440
Dammit, UCLA. I shouldn't have trusted you.

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:34.620
Mr. Crapper did improve the flushing
mechanism, though.

00:40:34.620 --> 00:40:38.760
In that same video, I also f***** up
and said that Ibn Sina was Arab,

00:40:38.760 --> 00:40:41.760
when he actually was Persian.
Sorry.

00:40:41.760 --> 00:40:46.980
In my Lighthouses video, I meant to
say John Brown, not James Brown.

00:40:46.980 --> 00:40:49.320
Shame, shame, shame, shame.

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:53.040
In my James Dean video, I called
Sal Mineo a gay man.

00:40:53.040 --> 00:40:55.200
He was actually bisexual.

00:40:55.200 --> 00:40:57.660
Sorry to bisexuals across the world.

00:40:57.660 --> 00:41:00.720
You can have your poor little&nbsp;
meow meow back, he's all yours.

00:41:00.720 --> 00:41:04.260
I got this one mixed up because when
reading the sources for that video,

00:41:04.260 --> 00:41:09.840
it was primarily sources from the 60s and 70s,
when it was really common to be

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:13.620
calling anyone with same-sex
attraction flat-out gay, so.

00:41:13.620 --> 00:41:14.640
Whoops.

00:41:14.640 --> 00:41:18.180
Anyway, are these offenses the
end of the world? No.

00:41:18.180 --> 00:41:21.540
And when they do pop up, I try my best
to put a note in the description or

00:41:21.540 --> 00:41:24.960
the comments to point it out,
so definitely check down there

00:41:24.960 --> 00:41:26.580
when you're watching a video,
just in case.

00:41:26.580 --> 00:41:29.700
I'm human. I've f***** up,
and by God, I'll do it again!

00:41:29.700 --> 00:41:34.320
But the point is, I'm well aware of
like, how serious my job is.

00:41:34.320 --> 00:41:38.040
And I don't know how other history
creators feel, but I feel like

00:41:38.040 --> 00:41:40.080
it's a really serious job.

00:41:40.080 --> 00:41:44.400
It's why, at least for now, I do
iterally every part of it by myself,

00:41:44.400 --> 00:41:48.420
so then I can hold myself accountable
for every part of the process.

00:41:48.420 --> 00:41:52.440
There is pros and cons to this, and
honestly, I know at some point

00:41:52.440 --> 00:41:56.160
I will need to get help,
but until then and even after,

00:41:56.160 --> 00:41:59.400
when I get folks in the comments
either pointing out when I oopsied

00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:03.960
on a fact, or adding more context
to something, I really appreciate it.

00:42:03.960 --> 00:42:08.040
And that's also why I honestly feel
kind of disgusted when people

00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:12.540
go online and frame themselves as
educators in order to get views,

00:42:12.540 --> 00:42:17.880
but all they do is post unsourced,
poorly researched, sensationalist junk.

00:42:17.880 --> 00:42:20.820
Because then as a result,
me and my history pals

00:42:20.820 --> 00:42:22.560
have to come in and clean the mess up.

00:42:22.560 --> 00:42:25.380
I guess that means that we'll never
run out of stuff to talk about, though.

00:42:25.380 --> 00:42:26.460
For better or for worse.

00:42:26.460 --> 00:42:29.460
The last thing I want you to get out
of this video is the idea that

00:42:29.460 --> 00:42:31.560
I'm making this to make myself look better,

00:42:31.560 --> 00:42:34.140
and that's not what I'm trying to do at all.

00:42:34.140 --> 00:42:35.520
I mean, look at my dunce hat.

00:42:35.520 --> 00:42:39.300
I just want to point these things out
to implore you to be vigilant, aware,

00:42:39.300 --> 00:42:41.340
and thoughtful about what you learn,

00:42:41.340 --> 00:42:44.760
and what you log into your
brain library as a fact.

00:42:44.760 --> 00:42:49.320
Don't be too afraid or too proud to
unlearn something, or acknowledge

00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:50.460
what you thought was wrong.

00:42:50.460 --> 00:42:54.720
And more than anything, these incidents
remind me that personally,

00:42:54.720 --> 00:42:57.180
I can always do better, too.

00:42:57.180 --> 00:43:01.980
I appreciate you for trusting me
with your learning, I really do,

00:43:01.980 --> 00:43:04.800
because that trust is a really valuable thing.

00:43:04.800 --> 00:43:11.580
So until next time, wash thy hands, wear
thy mask, and don't punch any babies.

00:43:11.580 --> 00:43:21.000
[electronic baroque&nbsp;piano end theme music]

